Lateinamerica in the Fight Against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
Unless we take decisive action against the crisis, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
Until now, the political reactions in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health their top priority.
Others, however, unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided their citizens with false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These state leaders decided in the midst of the tragedy to pursue a populist and divisive policy.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians must focus on improving the healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or congress centers, and strongly increasing testing capacities.
Moreover, Latin American countries must reject export controls on medical supply goods and other important resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) - in stark contrast to US President Donald Trump with his ruthless decision to freeze approximately $500 million in contributions to the WHO.
We need a stronger global cooperation of health authorities to increase testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines - in order to finally end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: not only has the Latin American domestic production been interrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses from the lack of tourism and fewer foreign remittances, as well as significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could trigger a contraction spiral together with the collapse of demand.
To prevent this, brave measures are required to protect household incomes.
It means transferring benefits to the crisis victims, including informal and independent workers who do not have access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relaxations for businesses are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and salaries protect both them and their employees during the crisis. They are therefore crucial for a quick economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, then the payment system – and with it the entire national economy – is at risk.
Many companies, particularly the small and medium-sized ones, will experience significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Deferred tax payments, payment deferrals, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This emergency requires not only unprecedented government guarantees for loans to ensure that banks continue to lend money, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and well-managed state banks can play a leading role in this.
From a general perspective, measures will likely vary by country, but overall, extraordinary budget resources will be required everywhere to accelerate recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without worsening health risks.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America is even tighter today than it was after the 2008 global financial crisis.
Therefore, budgetary burdens must be cushioned through budget adjustments in lower-priority areas.
However, there is a risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness, which can be reduced by the governments' promise to correct the higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, especially for the small and less developed Latin American countries, there is an urgent need for external support for household and balance of payments.
As both private companies and states take on higher deficits, the performance balances of the countries will likely deteriorate.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the largest reversals in modern financial market history – will exacerbate the problem.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing influence.
In many economies of the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to receive much more external support.
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role here.
It must address the short-term currency and budget needs of countries and continue to support their economies in this crisis, the duration of which is highly uncertain.
To do this, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a reissue of the IMF's global reserve currency – special drawing rights, which should reach a volume of one trillion SDR.
Although the SDRs are allocated to member countries according to their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a joint pool under the Fund's supervision.
In addition, the IMF could create the necessary capacity to meet the upcoming strong credit demand by doubling the volume of new credit agreements immediately.
And finally, the Fund must improve access to low-cost tools with rapid payment – such as its rapid financing instrument – or introduce new credit facilities for the pandemic because traditional IMF credit programs cannot be approved in time.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can pass on liquidity to central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all available instruments and create new ones if necessary to provide the financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
And finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursements in the region and tap high-liquidity global capital markets to be able to provide further budget support.
Under extraordinary circumstances and in countries without market access, official credit provision could be supplemented by a debt cut.
The MEB should also give countries guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – especially for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a crucial role in this.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is without precedent in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region can't afford delayed or inadequate reactions.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagoguery.
The crisis must not serve as an excuse to weaken our hard-fought citizens' rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and show what it can offer to citizens.
